{"title_page": "Terry Phelan", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Terry Phelan\n| image = \n| fullname = Terrence Phelan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1967|3|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 1984\u20131985\n| youthclubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C. Reserves and Youth Team|Leeds United]]\n| years1 = 1985\u20131986\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987\n| years3 = 1987\u20131992\n| years4 = 1992\u20131995\n| years5 = 1995\u20131997\n| years6 = 1997\u20132000\n| years7 = 1999\n| years8 = 2000\u20132001\n| years9 = 2001\n| years10 = 2001\u20132005\n| years11 = 2005\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| clubs2 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]\n| clubs3 = [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]\n| clubs4 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| clubs5 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| clubs6 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]\n| clubs9 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| clubs10 = [[Charleston Battery]]\n| clubs11 = [[Southern United FC|Otago United]]\n| caps1 = 14\n| caps2 = 45\n| caps3 = 159\n| caps4 = 104\n| caps5 = 15\n| caps6 = 25\n| caps7 = 14\n| caps8 = 18\n| caps9 = 8\n| caps10 = 39\n| caps11 = 6\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 1\n| goals4 = 2\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 2\n| goals9 = 0\n| goals10 = 0\n| goals11 = 0\n| totalcaps = 447\n| totalgoals = 5\n| nationalyears1 = 1987\n| nationalyears2 = 1990\n| nationalyears3 = 1990\n| nationalyears4 = 1991\u20132000\n| nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland U21]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-23 football team|Republic of Ireland U23]]\n| nationalteam3 = [[Republic of Ireland B national football team|Republic of Ireland B]]\n| nationalteam4 = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalcaps4 = 42\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Terrence Phelan''' (born 16 March 1967) is a former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|left-back]] from 1984 to 2009.\n\nHe played in the [[Premier League]] for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], as well as in the [[Football League]] for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]], [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. He finished his career abroad for [[Charleston Battery]] and [[Southern United FC|Otago United]]. He also made 42 appearances for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish national team]], whom he represented at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nDuring 2015, he was the head coach of [[Kerala Blasters]] of the [[Indian Super League]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/isl-2015-irishman-terry-phelan-appointed-new-head-coach-of-kerala-blasters-2490978.html|title=ISL 2015: Irishman Terry Phelan appointed new head coach of Kerala Blasters|publisher=First Post|date=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nPhelan started his career as part of the [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] youth system, and made 19 appearances for Leeds in the [[1985-86 in English football|1985\u201386]] season, but was released on a free transfer by Leeds manager [[Billy Bremner]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Leeds United player profile \u2013 Terry Phelan| work=leeds-fans.org.uk| url=http://www.leeds-fans.org.uk/leeds/players/322.html| accessdate=30 May 2006}}</ref> Phelan then spent a year at [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], earning a move to top division [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] a year later.\n\nIn his first season at Wimbledon, Phelan was a member of the team which won the [[FA Cup]] with a shock win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[1988 FA Cup Final|final]]. He also helped Wimbledon finish seventh in the league on two occasions during his time there.\n\nAfter five years at Wimbledon in which he made 198 appearances, Phelan was transferred to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] for \u00a32.5 million at the start of the [[1992-93 in English football|1992\u201393 season]], equalling the British record transfer fee for a defender as well as equalling the club's record fee. At City, Phelan made 122 appearances over three and a half seasons. Arguably the best goal of Phelan's career came at [[Maine Road]] for City in an FA Cup tie against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] when the full-back ran the length of the pitch skipping several challenges and keeping his cool to slot home.\n\nPhelan moved to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in November 1995, where he spent two years on the fringes of the first team (playing just 15 times in the league) before moving to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], where he played regularly under [[Joe Royle]], until he suffered an injury from which he took nearly 18 months to recover.<ref>{{cite web | title=Everton Past Player Fact File \u2013 Terry Phelan| work=Toffeeweb| url=http://www.toffeeweb.com/players/past/Phelan.html| accessdate=30 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\nDuring Phelan's injury, [[Walter Smith]] took over as Everton manager (after [[Howard Kendall]]'s third spell as manager lasted just one season), and did not select Phelan following his recovery, instead loaning him to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Phelan moved to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in February 2000, and was part of the Fulham team which won promotion to the [[FA Premier League|Premier League]] in 2001. However, Phelan was released by Fulham following promotion, having just made two league appearances that campaign.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|6318|2000|name=Terry Phelan|access-date=11 November 2014}}</ref> Phelan then had a short spell with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] before moving to the United States, where he played for [[Charleston Battery]] and also coached young players. In October 2005, Phelan was named as player-coach of [[Southern United FC|Otago United]] in the [[NZFC|New Zealand Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Terry Phelan arrives in Otago| work=NZCity News| url=http://home.nzcity.co.nz/news/default.asp?id=55617&cat=1005&c=w| accessdate=30 May 2006 }}</ref> He remained as coach for four seasons up until the end of the 2008\u201309 season when, owing to poor results, he was replaced by his assistant Malcolm Fleming for the 2009\u201310 season.\n\n==International career==\nHe made 42 appearances for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish national team]], whom he represented at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Coaching career==\nPhelan is one of the coaches at the new Templegate Training Academy in Ardwick, Manchester.<ref>Manchester Evening News, 25 June 2013</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2015, Phelan was appointed as a Technical Director of [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]' grassroots programme. On 1 November 2015, he was made the head coach of the Blasters after [[Peter Taylor (footballer, born 1953)|Peter Taylor]] was sacked. He returned to his previous role when [[Steve Coppell]] was appointed as head coach.\n\n==Honours==\n'''Wimbledon'''\n*[[FA Cup]]: [[FA Cup Final 1988|1988]]\n\n'''Fulham'''\n*[[Football League First Division]]: [[2000\u201301 Football League|2000\u201301]]\n\n'''Charleston Battery'''\n*[[USL First Division|USL A-League]]: 2003\n*[[Southern Derby]]: 2003 2005\n\n'''Awards'''\n*[[Football League|Football League Fourth Division PFA Team of the Year]]: 1986\u201387\n*[[FAI International Football Awards|FAI Young International Player of the Year]]: 1992\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Republic of Ireland international footballers born outside the Republic of Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{1986\u201387 Football League Fourth Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{FAI Young International Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Republic of Ireland squad 1994 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Kerala Blasters FC head coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phelan, Terry}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Charleston Battery players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Otago United players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swansea City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon F.C. players]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Kerala Blasters FC head coaches]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League head coaches]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Terry Phelan\n| image = \n| fullname = Terrence Phelan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1967|3|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 1984\u20131985\n| youthclubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C. Reserves and Youth Team|Leeds United]]\n| years1 = 1985\u20131986\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987\n| years3 = 1987\u20131992\n| years4 = 1992\u20131995\n| years5 = 1995\u20131997\n| years6 = 1997\u20132000\n| years7 = 1999\n| years8 = 2000\u20132001\n| years9 = 2001\n| years10 = 2001\u20132005\n| years11 = 2005\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| clubs2 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]\n| clubs3 = [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]\n| clubs4 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| clubs5 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| clubs6 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]\n| clubs9 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| clubs10 = [[Charleston Battery]]\n| clubs11 = [[Southern United FC|Otago United]]\n| caps1 = 14\n| caps2 = 45\n| caps3 = 159\n| caps4 = 104\n| caps5 = 15\n| caps6 = 25\n| caps7 = 14\n| caps8 = 18\n| caps9 = 8\n| caps10 = 39\n| caps11 = 6\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 1\n| goals4 = 2\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 2\n| goals9 = 0\n| goals10 = 0\n| goals11 = 0\n| totalcaps = 447\n| totalgoals = 5\n| nationalyears1 = 1987\n| nationalyears2 = 1990\n| nationalyears3 = 1990\n| nationalyears4 = 1991\u20132000\n| nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland U21]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Republic of Ireland national under-23 football team|Republic of Ireland U23]]\n| nationalteam3 = [[Republic of Ireland B national football team|Republic of Ireland B]]\n| nationalteam4 = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalcaps4 = 42\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2015\n| managerclubs1 = [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Terrence Phelan''' (born 16 March 1967) is a former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|left-back]] from 1984 to 2009.\n\nHe played in the [[Premier League]] for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], as well as in the [[Football League]] for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]], [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. He finished his career abroad for [[Charleston Battery]] and [[Southern United FC|Otago United]]. He also made 42 appearances for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish national team]], whom he represented at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nDuring 2015, he was the head coach of [[Kerala Blasters]] of the [[Indian Super League]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/isl-2015-irishman-terry-phelan-appointed-new-head-coach-of-kerala-blasters-2490978.html|title=ISL 2015: Irishman Terry Phelan appointed new head coach of Kerala Blasters|publisher=First Post|date=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nPhelan started his career as part of the [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] youth system, and made 19 appearances for Leeds in the [[1985-86 in English football|1985\u201386]] season, but was released on a free transfer by Leeds manager [[Billy Bremner]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Leeds United player profile \u2013 Terry Phelan| work=leeds-fans.org.uk| url=http://www.leeds-fans.org.uk/leeds/players/322.html| accessdate=30 May 2006}}</ref> Phelan then spent a year at [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], earning a move to top division [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] a year later.\n\nIn his first season at Wimbledon, Phelan was a member of the team which won the [[FA Cup]] with a shock win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[1988 FA Cup Final|final]]. He also helped Wimbledon finish seventh in the league on two occasions during his time there.\n\nAfter five years at Wimbledon in which he made 198 appearances, Phelan was transferred to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] for \u00a32.5 million at the start of the [[1992-93 in English football|1992\u201393 season]], equalling the British record transfer fee for a defender as well as equalling the club's record fee. At City, Phelan made 122 appearances over three and a half seasons. Arguably the best goal of Phelan's career came at [[Maine Road]] for City in an FA Cup tie against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] when the full-back ran the length of the pitch skipping several challenges and keeping his cool to slot home.\n\nPhelan moved to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in November 1995, where he spent two years on the fringes of the first team (playing just 15 times in the league) before moving to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], where he played regularly under [[Joe Royle]], until he suffered an injury from which he took nearly 18 months to recover.<ref>{{cite web | title=Everton Past Player Fact File \u2013 Terry Phelan| work=Toffeeweb| url=http://www.toffeeweb.com/players/past/Phelan.html| accessdate=30 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\nDuring Phelan's injury, [[Walter Smith]] took over as Everton manager (after [[Howard Kendall]]'s third spell as manager lasted just one season), and did not select Phelan following his recovery, instead loaning him to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Phelan moved to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in February 2000, and was part of the Fulham team which won promotion to the [[FA Premier League|Premier League]] in 2001. However, Phelan was released by Fulham following promotion, having just made two league appearances that campaign.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|6318|2000|name=Terry Phelan|access-date=11 November 2014}}</ref> Phelan then had a short spell with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] before moving to the United States, where he played for [[Charleston Battery]] and also coached young players. In October 2005, Phelan was named as player-coach of [[Southern United FC|Otago United]] in the [[NZFC|New Zealand Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Terry Phelan arrives in Otago| work=NZCity News| url=http://home.nzcity.co.nz/news/default.asp?id=55617&cat=1005&c=w| accessdate=30 May 2006 }}</ref> He remained as coach for four seasons up until the end of the 2008\u201309 season when, owing to poor results, he was replaced by his assistant Malcolm Fleming for the 2009\u201310 season.\n\n==International career==\nHe made 42 appearances for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Irish national team]], whom he represented at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Coaching career==\nPhelan is one of the coaches at the new Templegate Training Academy in Ardwick, Manchester.<ref>Manchester Evening News, 25 June 2013</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2015, Phelan was appointed as a Technical Director of [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]' grassroots programme. On 1 November 2015, he was made the head coach of the Blasters after [[Peter Taylor (footballer, born 1953)|Peter Taylor]] was sacked. He returned to his previous role when [[Steve Coppell]] was appointed as head coach.\n\n==Honours==\n'''Wimbledon'''\n*[[FA Cup]] (1): [[FA Cup Final 1988|1988]]\n\n'''Fulham'''\n*[[Football League First Division]] (1): [[2000\u201301 Football League|2000\u201301]]\n\n'''Charleston Battery'''\n*[[USL First Division|USL A-League]] (1): 2003\n*[[Southern Derby]] (2): 2003 2005\n\n'''Awards'''\n*[[Football League|Football League Fourth Division PFA Team of the Year]] (1): 1986\u201387\n*[[FAI International Football Awards|FAI Young International Player of the Year]] (1): 1992\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Republic of Ireland international footballers born outside the Republic of Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{1986\u201387 Football League Fourth Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{FAI Young International Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Republic of Ireland squad 1994 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Kerala Blasters FC head coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phelan, Terry}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland association footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Charleston Battery players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Otago United players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swansea City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon F.C. players]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Kerala Blasters FC head coaches]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League head coaches]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category: